	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />This is called "ateji" (当て字) and is basically a form of rebus used with kanji. The practice started from the view that it was necessary to have kanji equivalents of foreign loadwords (<!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_words_of_Portuguese_origin">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_w ... ese_origin</a><!-- m -->)
<br />
<br />I guess its used for the same reason you would say "effervescent" instead of "fizzy", a bunch of 80-stroke kanji that haven't been used since the US was a British colony is more impressive than plain old katakana. It's also fun to apply to your name and sign your Japanese 9 homework with it.
<br />
<br />P.S. Suprising that no one mentioned <em>Salamander</em>.
<br />
<br />P.P.S. For the record, <em>Gryzor</em> was the name of the Speccy/C64 ports of the game by Ocean.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
